THE ANDRIA

15. The Andria was the first play which Terence pro- duced—the one he read to Caecilius at dinner, thereby gaining that poet's esteem (see §3 of Suetonius’ Life of Terence, p. 42 above). It was in the main a translation of the Andria of Menander. The latter play, however, seems to have been virtually a second recension of the Perinthia, which Menander had written early in his ,career3 and Terence preferred to follow the earlier piece at some points, One of these placeS, the ancient commentator Donatus tells uS, was the first act, which in Menander's Andria consisted of a monologue by the old man, while in the Perinthia he was represented as talking to his wife. Terence substituted a freedman as the second character in the dialogue. Donatus further tells us that the characters Carinus and Burria did not appear in Menander’s Andria, and it has been plausibly suggested that Terence got them from the Perinthia.
